Disa Sariola, CMPS 6790 Tulane Fall 2023

This project is done partly based on my RA duties for the Center for Community-Engaged AI, and the primary data source is not open source but can be requested from the authors of the paper. All related work and code are hosted on a private github page, to which Professor Mattei has rights to. I am working alone for this Fall 2023 Data Science Project. However, there will be some input from the CCEA on this project, as they are the stakeholders of the larger research project.

There are four datasets that I am using for this project. My approach is to have one main dataset that I am enriching from other sources, this main dataset is from the paper Is It Harder for Older Workers to Find Jobs? New and Improved Evidence from a Field Experiment (1). The data enrichment is done with Unemployment Percentage (2), GeoPy Nonimatim (3) and Age Discrimination Laws per state from the paper "Do State Laws Protecting Older Workers from Discrimination Reduce Age Discrimination in Hiring? Evidence from a Field Experiment" (4). As a note (4) was manually interpreted from the page 16 table on these laws, and binary encoded. For further insights, that csv file can be found in the data folder under the name 'StateLawsAge.csv" The main dataset contains 40,208 resume applications, that were generated for a correspondence study to uncover age discrimination in job application. The generated resumes have been formulated to have as many controlled variables as possible and to seem realistic as possible. Each resume contains the applicants name, age, contact information, the job they applied to, their skill level, educational background, special skills, city and whether they got a callback. For each application, the main measurement is whether the resume received a callback.

The unemployment percentage data is from the bureau of labor statistics and contains the employment and unemployment percentage for each respective state for each year. As the main data concerns only 2015, that is the only year I am interested in.

GeoPy Nonimatim is used to fetch the state for each city, as the resume applications contain only the city where the application was made. As the application corresponds to the location of the applicant, we only need to fetch one states information per application.

The enrichment dataset is from the paper "Do State Laws Protecting Older Workers from Discrimination Reduce Age Discrimination in Hiring? Evidence from a Field Experiment" (4), and were manually extracted and then encoded to be categorical and binary. The research questions I am looking to answer are the following.

  1. Is there a relationship between gender, age, employment status when it comes to callbacks? How do these statistics change between states?
  2. Does a states unemployment rate affect the callback rates?
  3. Can we predict callbacks, and how accurately can we do this?
  4. Does enriching the original data with unemployment of the state and age discrimination laws affect the accuracy?
  5. Does Age affect the callback prediction bias?

Currently the next steps are to divide the data into an 80/20 split, and use that 20% as testing data that contains the original distribution of the data. The remaining 80% will be divided into several datasets to train Logistic Regression, Random Forest and MLP classifiers on. Each classifier will be trained with four datasets with two versions. The first set with data that contains the original distribution of the data, second with a balanced age group representation, the third a group where the callback rates are balanced to be equal between the young and old group, and fourth where we balance the callback rates irregardless of age. Additionally, the data will be resampled from the three applications to each ad, such that we can see whether the inclusion of results for each group will have an effect on the callback rates. All datasets will additionally have a model that contains age and one that does not contain the age as a feature.

These will be then tested using the Positive Rate difference (5) between the two groups, the Accuracy (i.e. (True Positive + True Negative)/Number of Applicants) (5), The False Positive Rate Difference and False Negative Rate difference (i.e. Pr(Positive Rate for young) - Pr(Positive Rate for old), 0 means there is no bias), and the skew for the effect (False Positive rate for young vs False positive rate for old and False Negative rate for young vs False Negative rate for old, so whether the error is towards the group or works against them).

The aim here is to see how strong the effet of age is on the callback rates, how do rebalancing and data manipulationg affect the learning outcomes.

The parsing and cleaning of the data was rather straightforward, the most difficult part was deciding which columns to drop. Thus, the current choice of columns is not final,but there were originally 142 columns. I was originally using modular one-time cleaning scripts for my data and some manual precursory cleaning, and had to reformat them to a jupyter notebook form. This caused mostly a visual challenge to the viewer, as it causes unnecessary clutter. All these scripts can be found in the scripts folder.

As can be seen above, the raw data has 138 columns. The adtitles are not very clean, and there is a lot of redundant data. We have multiple dummy columns, for example the age group, and separate 'middlemale', 'oldmale', 'oldfemale', 'middlefemale' and many others. So the start is to clean these. The cleaning and its details can be found in the helper_scripts.py that is imported in the beginning.

The description for this is that we use regular expressions to clean adtitles, and we limit to the columns 'state', 'zipcode','city','agegroup', 'gender', 'employment', 'occupation','template', 'spanish','extra_qualifs', 'internshipflag','customerservice','cpr','techskills','wpm','grammar','college', 'employeemonth','volunteer', 'skill', 'callback', 'adtitle' from this original data set. We are also missing data, we have the city but we have no state. So we use geopy Nonimatim to add the state based on the city. We combine some of the columns, to remove redundancy. If we need to create dummies lately, we can do that with pandas (and will), but at the moment we are just striving for a clean dataset that can be used for different purposes.

As part of the criteria for milestone 2 is to bring in extra data, I have chosen to bring in State laws for Age Discrimination. This can be found in (4) in table form and that data has been parsed into a csv manually and then encoded in a categorical and binary form.

Additionally, we enrich this dataset with the unemployment percentages for the state in question. These extra columns end up as 'hs_diploma_state', 'college_diploma_state', 'some_college_state','unemployment_perc', 'ADL Minimum Firm Size', 'ADL Larger Damages than ADEA', 'DDL Minimum Firm Size','DDL Larger Damages than ADA','DDL Broader Definition of Disability'.

These correspond to the the rate of high school graduation, the college graduation rate, the college attendance rate, the state unemployment percentage, the minimum firm size for the age discrimination laws to apply, whether these ADL damages are larger than The Age Discrimination in Employment Act damages, Disability Discrimination Act Damages larger than ADA, and whether DDL has a broader definition of disability. As a precursor here it is important to remember the state vs. federal laws. While there are federal level laws, state laws might be more punitive.

The above two graphs show the z-scored callback rates per employment sector per state, the first one shows bars and we separate state and skill levels. The second graph takes across all graphs and just shows the general z-scored distribution for the data, to give more emphasis on the relationship between the unemployment percentage and the callback rates. By z-scoring the unemployment data, we can see that when we compare a states statistics to the mean, that among the states we have multiple outliers. However, we can only really make some assumptions based on these and we can not comment on the causation of these deviations.

For Graph 1, the unemployment percentage on the y-axis being negative is desirable as it means the states unemployment percentage is lower than the mean. Meanwhile, for the callback rates on the y-axis, a positive value is more desirable. There does not seem to be a clear indication that the unemployment percentage has a relationship with the number of callback received. We can see that between states, the labor market is very different, for example Pennsylvania there seems to be a high demand for highly educated employed administrative personnel. In New York, despite a higher education it is much more difficult and unlikely to receive a callback. For Utah, you are more likely to receive a callback no matter the applicants education level.

For Graph 2, we can see that there is some effect where when unemployment rates are at the mean or slightly above it, the callback rates are below the mean. However, this effect is not continous and does not constitute a trend. So, there is some relationship where deviation from the mean employment irregardless of it being negative or positive results in a boost in callback rates on average. This is difficult to say what is causing it, as the local labor market distribution is not being taken into account.

As can be seen, the data is currently very heavy on the no-callbacks. This means we have to rebalance the set, so any learning can be validated. The choice here is to for now do random sampling, as the data contains 3 applications for each job. So, we resample with two criteria and also use the original dataset. Below is the original dataset and its distribution of callbacks across all applications.

Length of no callbacks for resampling once:  7244 , Percentage: 83.61%
Length of callbacks for resampling once:  1420 , Percentage: 16.39%

For the first resampling, the above function call randomly selects a single instance for each job application. After that we separate the dataset into two, the majority and the minority groups. These are done according to the callback = 1 being majority and callback = 0 being the minority. As can be seen, we end up with a much smaller dataset, that is slightly more balanced.

In [11]:
random_sample_adtitles_df_two = random_sample_adtitles(df_cleaned, 2)

df_majority_two = random_sample_adtitles_df_two[random_sample_adtitles_df_two.callback==0]
df_minority_two = random_sample_adtitles_df_two[random_sample_adtitles_df_two.callback==1]

print('\nLength of no callbacks for resampling twice: ',len(df_majority_two), f', Percentage: {np.round((len(df_majority_two)/len(random_sample_adtitles_df_two)) *100, 2)}%')
print('Length of callbacks for resampling twice: ', len(df_minority_two), f', Percentage: {np.round((len(df_minority_two)/len(random_sample_adtitles_df_two)) *100, 2)}%')

Length of no callbacks for resampling twice:  13986 , Percentage: 80.71%
Length of callbacks for resampling twice:  3342 , Percentage: 19.29%

For the second resampling, the above function call randomly selects an instance of an application, then if that application has an instance with a callback, we add also that to our set. If the first chosen instance was one without a callback, and there is no application for that ad with a callback, we continue as normal. After that we separate the dataset into two again, the majority and the minority groups. These are done according to the callback = 1 being majority and callback = 0 being the minority. As can be seen, we end up with a much smaller dataset, that is slightly more balanced.

Above are the pre-eliminary results, for training the different classifiers for the the resampled datasets. These can be seen to constitute the subgroup four, where we train the classifiers on a balanced number of callbacks and no callbacks irregardless of age. As a note, these still have the age feature. As can be seen, the sampling based on callback or no callback seems to have a marginal effect on the results. The Logistic Regression Classifier seems to perform the best. For the above results, it can be seen that rebalancing the number of callbacks to be equal between the sets and making the set smaller, does not seem to have much effect on the accuracy of the predictor.
